</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAPERBACKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE KWINKAN by Mudrooroo (Angus & Robertson/HarperCollins: $10; 130 pp., 
paperback original). The latest novel by Aboriginal writer Mudrooroo takes the 
form of a series of depositions by a would-be big-shot.The narrator's failure 
as a businessman and political candidate in Queensland puts him at the mercy of 
the party bosses, who send him to investigate a Pacific island group that's 
about to become an independent state. The inept fixer wastes his time pursuing 
the heiress of the island's de facto ruling family, whom he compares to a 
Kwinkan, a siren in Aboriginal myths. Despite his dreams of glory, the narrator 
remains a pawn in a game waged by the heiress, a Japanese businesswoman and an 
Aboriginal undercover agent, in a stinging portrait of intransigent, 
post-colonial racism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA032794-0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 026577 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
March 27, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 9; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
135 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAPERBACKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 THE REVENGE OF GOD: The Resurgence of Islam, Christianity and Judaism in the 
Modern World by Gilles Kepel, translated from the French by Alan Braley (The 
Pennsylvania State University Press: $14.95.; 215 pp., paperback original). 
Kepel's well-researched study examines religious revival movements in Islam, 
Judaism and Christianity (both American evangelical Protestantism and European 
Catholicism). Followers of each movement seek to remold society by repudiating 
"Godless" rationalism, which they blame for the erosion of some traditional 
values in the modern world. Kepel carefully notes differences, as well as 
similarities (Orthodox Jewish activists don't seek converts, as evangelical 
Christians do) in this intelligent, often disturbing look at an increasingly 
widespread phenomenon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
