<HEADLINE>
<P>
RECORD RACK: 'PLAYBOYS': A TWIST ON LOS LOBOS; *** 1/2 LATIN PLAYBOYS, "LATIN 
PLAYBOYS"; SLASH/WARNER BROS.  
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE HOCHMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 On 1992's remarkable "Kiko," Los Lobos employed a vast array of sonic 
surprises to give its songs a magic realism twist. This side project teaming 
Lobos' David Hidalgo and Louie Perez with keyboardist Mitchell Froom and 
guitarist Tchad Blake -- the producer and engineer of "Kiko" -- is all 
twist.Yet it too is quite magical. 
</P>
<P>
 If short on actual songs, the album is full of bracing sonic vignettes, with a 
variety of instruments and found sounds used to paint pictures of street 
celebrations or Mexican villages or Chinese landscapes. 
</P>
<P>
 Even when the numbers take more traditional song structure, Perez's lyrics are 
almost haiku-like in their spare imagery, and Hidalgo's soulfully serene vocals 
are as effective as on Los Lobos' more concrete material. 
</P>
<P>
 The lack of the celebratory, rootsy foundation separates this from full Los 
Lobos projects. But seen as a one-off project, it makes a fine complement to 
the band's catalogue -- a chance to examine more closely one of the band's 
multiple facets. And seen as a continuation of "Kiko," it represents ambition 
and growth on par with that shown by U2 in its '90s albums. Stunning. 
</P>
<P>
 New albums are rated on a scale of one star (poor), two stars (fair), three 
stars (good) and four stars (excellent). STEVE HOCHMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
