<HEADLINE>
<P>
FLOWERS, DRUMS END COOK ISLANDS ELECTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The leader of Cook Islands marked his election victory with flowers and drums 
on Friday, but one of his ministers headed for defeat for trying to bring a 
McDonald's to one of the most isolated spots in the Pacific. 
</P>
<P>
 Triumphant Prime Minister Sir Geoffrey Henry said an opposition campaign 
highlighting allegations of corruption and financial mismanagement had little 
impact on the 11,000 voters in the 15-island group that stretches over 
thousands of square miles of ocean south of Hawaii. 
</P>
<P>
 People were more concerned about health, education and jobs than charges of 
tax-haven swindles and mismanagement of the construction of a $50-million 
Sheraton Hotel, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Minister of Marine Resources Ben Toma lost the island constituency of Manihiki 
by five votes, but may win it back when special and postal votes are counted. 
</P>
<P>
 Toma had campaigned to bring the McDonald's hamburger chain to the remote 
island, five hours flying time from Rarotonga. 
</P>
